comment:
U struck a chord with the "What do you have to be sad about?" comment.
Logical depression at least makes sense.
When it happens to me or my wife.
It can be figured out a dealt with and has a sort of origin.
The fact that the brain takes something one can usually deal with
And turns up your system to 11
So the molehill becomes a mountain.
Easy peasy... sorta.
But...
When Clinical Depression hits... üò®
This is when your just chugging along and the world is just a turd sandwich but hey who cares because love exists and we shall overcome and magic gummies are legal and TRANSFORMERS toys are awesome and life is good.
Then for no F@#$ing reason at all, your brain turns against you and your soul falls out.
üò≥
And. It. Won't. Stop. Being.... difficult.
You cannot talk to it.
All you want is sleep, weed, hugs and the quiet darkness of the Batcave of Solitude.
It cannot be reasoned with.
It won't just stop.
The meds help a bit.

But man does it get in the way of Life.
Inconvenient. To say the least.
Dangerous, more often than anyone knows.

Be good.

comment:
Hearing you joke about mental health kinda casually is what helps me the most. It's the approach I take to it, sad amusement, and it doesn't feel performative because it affected your work when you didn't want it to. It doesn't feel like it's intended to raise awareness, it's just being straight with your audience. And that's the kind of thing I appreciate from like youtubers or that athlete girl talking about it. Like at least with top youtubers the schedule being interupted isn't going to screw them over financially, but it makes the point that for the rest of us, or with athletes or traditional celebs traditional systems, those systems aren't designed to deal with breakdowns or the effect they have on people. 

On the other hand, when Dodie made that video a few years ago about dissociation, while she was, it was an aspect of mental health and depression that was rarely seen, and it was cathartic for me. And later her video of the pandemics effects on her, on everyone really, being similar. That's the kind of thing...well I know it must take a lot out of them to expose that aspect of themselves, but I appreciate that. It makes it more real than just a post of text.

comment: I love that celebrities are coming out and speaking about their mental health. I think many people feel validated and embolden to stand up for themselves and to ask for what they need. There is one small caveat to that. The average person doesn't enjoy the same job security, and protections against discrimination that come with being a celebrity. I have experienced discrimination as recently as 2018. I was in a graduate program for clinical counseling and my advisor and director of the program found out I have bipolar, I was ultimately forced to leave the program as a result. I have also been denied/lost employment for requesting a set schedule so I could schedule therapies and get good sleep to stay healthy. They claimed the rotating schedules were company policy. Even with ADA stating that they are required to provide reasonable supports and accommodations. Actors, musicians, artists do not face those same barriers. I do think it's helpful for them to come out and normalize the struggle of mental health.

He said he might as well be in therapy 24/7 if he wasn't happy as he had the perfect life. That's to misunderstand how mental health issues work. You can have a dream life yet still be in mental agony. Humans are very complicated things and our brains work in strange ways. Mental health issues can hit anyone at any time. That's why talking about mental health is so important - so that people feel that they can talk about it if they're struggling, and that it's nothing to be ashamed of.

comment:
I have _so_ , *SO* many feelings around mental health awareness, and as someone who has dealt with severe mental health issues/is heavily medicated/has been involuntarily hospitalized, im am sick and tired of people TALKING about mental illness. The time for talking is over; *it's now time to fucking **_DO_** something.*



The current state of public psychiatric hospitals and wards is so horribly mismanaged, underfunded, understaffed and absolutely deplorable considering the wealth of this country. The people kept in psychiatric wards have NOTHING. They have no voice, they have no strength, they have no influence. We are treated like sick, dying livestock that needs to be quarantined and forgotten about, left to die. Only 38% of public psych hospitals even have a fucking crisis prevention team. From the 2018 NMHSS survey, 15 states had their inpatient facilities operated at or over 100% capacity meaning there are more patients than beds.

We are kept in the most dark, cramped, cold buildings. They are not built for rehabilitation, but for _containment._  It is a literal prison; the only difference is that instead of being beaten by a CO you're restrained/sedated by nurses. In 2018, about 50% of involuntary admissions to public psych hospitals had a criminal legal status. The links between mental illness, substance abuse, psychiatric hospitals, and prison are deep and have a lot of crossover.

Link for the stats; honestly I didn't even scratch the _surface_ 
https://www.samhsa.gov/data/sites/default/files/reports/rpt29388/2019_NMHSS/2019-NMHSS-R.pdf
https://www.samhsa.gov/data/sites/default/files/cbhsq-reports/NMHSS-2018.pdf



I am _extremely_ lucky that I was able to get out, but I will never forget the fear I felt. I remember at my hearing (because I was there involuntarily, there was basically a little "hearing" that was done to judge whether or not I needed to stay) I calmly, respectfully, and intelligently gave my case, but the judge never even _looked at me_. It was as if I wasn't even there; I had never been so humiliated, and I felt pure terror believing I would never be able to get out. You are truly not seen as a human being by those who don't work with you everyday. There are more than enough stories that can be found of others who have been in psych wards that showcase what it's like living in such a hellhole. 

We need to be getting more momentum for policies and changes that can be made; thankfully there are some working on that. https://mentalillnesspolicy.org/ is a great site that gives statistics on serious mental illness to give guidance to those that can actually help them. When talks of mental illness are brought up, THIS is the kind of thing that needs to be highlighted and focused on.


I am so _sick and tired_ of people talking. *it's time to start DOING SOMETHING*

comment:
Glad that mental health is being more publicized. The brain is a crazy organ. One of the natural things that the brain does is create stress. The brain wants to be challenged. When there is no challenge or external stress factors  to make the brain think. For example, physical exertion, socializing and academic goals (school or personal). If there is no stress for long enough The brain starts to re-wire it‚Äôs self, possibly shrink in clinically depressed individuals, and makes it harder to do those external stressors to help ‚Äúrecharge‚Äù the brain, making it re-wire more. And the downward spiral continues. 
All of that being said we live in a society where being the victim is cool. You probably can walk down any crowded area, have a conversation with someone and eventually they would either say that they are bipolar, have anxiety, have PTSD, or sometimes they‚Äôll say they have clinical depression. (Which is rare but likely) when in actuality they in fact do not have any diagnosis of any of these mental illnesses. 
Talk to any combat veteran who has been diagnosed with PTSD and discuss the symptoms they experience, you might find that it‚Äôs miles away what other people claim to have experience. 
This is not a comment to put down those who have mental illnesses, it‚Äôs just to make light that there are real people suffering from these experiences and others just speaking out of their ass for clout.

comment: I understand "Rich or Wealthy" people deal with things but I will never understand a lot of them because "Money" the number of things it solves in life that takes a lot of stress away. I understand people say with money come other problems and for public figures like actors and famous people I can understand with people always prying into your life is a lot. I was laid off unexpectedly during Covid from my job after getting the highest rating for performance you could and has only happened twice in the company. The reason wasn't due to Covid but because they lost a major contract and wanted to put someone else in my position (Different Contract) that made 4x the amount I did to bring the company more money (This company is pretty much gone now and lost the contract for letting me go). This was right after buying myself a vehicle and I am still going to college. I was really stressed out at first from it. Unemployment didn't cover my bills. My mother thankfully helped me out some until I got the increase from gov aid. Got a job offer a few months ago requiring an S+ which I got after a month of studying and now have a new job on a 5-year contract making twice as much as I did before with the company willing to pay for all my future schooling and certifications I would like. I understand life is rough, but don't tell me if I didn't have 2-5mil I wouldn't be set to not have to worry about anything money-wise in life again which for me seems like everything right now other than family. The past year hit by covid and before that hit by hurricane Michael. Life has been intense the last few years but it is on the up which I am thankful for and the extra money I am making will go to paying back my mother, school, savings, and investments. This time around I will also get my savings account to 10k instead of 1k in case anything crazy happens and always keeping 1k in my checking account for now own. I don't wanna have to be laid off again when things were going really good and have to worry about things like a did again or at least have something to fall back on a little so I don't have to worry as much.

comment:
My problem with celebrities; specifically the richest, more famous and most likely to continue to find employment, is: all of us have problems. You, using your "issues" to write a narrative about mental health, is using your social influence to create more capital gains for your platform/media releases, knowing your name alone will generate more revenue. If celebrities truly want to speak about mental health, they should use their influence to get a true message out from their productions rather than try to relate to the common man in social media. 
It's pandering to think Ryan Reynolds and I  have anywhere near the same ability to handle our individual struggles. Maybe some celebrities do need help, like all humans might, they aren't super-humans. The difference is they have the ability to help themselves infinitely more ($$ bills), and subsequently others (through media), where individuals rarely see any support or difference in their lives if they lack these fundamental structures, from income, to family/friends/supporters. We aren't the same and trying to think you are is ignoring the disparity between socioeconomic power of individuals, no matter how well meaning either side is.

DISCLAIMER: Ryan Reynolds - I love this man, no matter how many worlds apart we truly are.

comment:
Mental health is something I have been struggling with for about 10 years now.  Over this last year and a half, I have just been bombarded with stressors like most people.  This time last year I was emitted to the hospital for being suicidal.  While I am not currently suicidal struggling with Massive Anxiety and Depression every day could be that day where just one too many things fail or don't go the way I need them to from being back in that dark place.  I'm happy more people are talking about mental health and trying to change the mindset of how people see mental health.

To all those who have this struggle to please reach out to someone anyone for help. Just remember YOU ARE NOT ALONE!

A song that got me to finally give in to seeking help was a song called "The Humbling River" by Puscifer.

comment: Phil, thank you. I don't usually don't lump myself into the mental health awareness talk because I don't often think of myself having an issue, but I do. It's one you highlighted today and it's one that the last year, in particular, had me put more into focus. I am 49 and a husband/father. For my entire life I have been some kind of an entertainer to varying degrees of success. For the last 10 years I have been a musician. A write some songs/learn some covers/grab my guitar and go play at a bar guy.  For years it was evening life only but then I got laid off and made the decision with my family to go full time. So, for the past 4 years I have been full steam ahead, until the pandemic. I took a more regular job to pick up the slack. Anyway, here is my point. I have every reason to be happy. I have amazing friends, a loving family, a grown son who is fantastic and most of all, I make a living almost entirely doing what I love. It's a struggle, yes, but on good days I feel lucky. I have some fans and venues that like to hear me play. People listen to the music I write  But that depression creeps in. Even when I know I am doing enough, I beat myself up inside. I realize that no amount of success or fan-love could ever change that. That this thing inside me will be inside me no matter how great my world is... because it's pretty great now. It comes back to that old saying, "no matter where you turn, there you are". No matter how beautiful a day, we do all carry the capacity inside of us to be horrible to ourselves. So, thank you for highlighting that today. Good luck in the new space and never stop being awesome.

comment:
Disclaimer: It's a wall, but I thought about all of it. Might be worth a read.

Maybe I'm being negative, because I can understand and appreciate the sentiment, but here's how I feel about the idea of celebrities talking about their mental health helping regular people. 

If you're someone who, like me, doesn't look up to people because they're famous, and your mental health situation is caused by issues famous people don't have to deal with (poverty, for example), it does require that said depressed regular person already be in a mindset of wanting to look for silver linings and things to hang their hope on for a celebrity's confessions to have much of an impact.

The problem with mental health issues, depression in particular, is that sufferers don't spend all or most of their time in a hopeful mindset. I mean just be real, I'm sure you know from first and secondhand experience that when someone is on a downswing, they're not unlikely, when hearing about a celebrity/more successful person's depression, to compare in every way how much worse their situation is objectively and how few options they have compared to the celebrity. It's naive to imagine that every depressed person is just primed and waiting to hear words of support to jump-start their recovery. Depressed people often don't even want to listen.

I've just had a fundamental aversion to celebrity worship my whole life, and so many things, this example included, feel like extensions of that. I feel like, to the extent the kinds of benefits you're suggesting exist in this case, there's a lot more post-hoc, subconscious rationalization going on in holding up mainly celebrity stories as examples than people realize.

We have the internet - it's more feasible than ever to share the stories of regular people instead of rich and famous ones. I don't think the reason we still choose celebrity stories is based on an honest analysis of efficacy - we just have an obsession with celebrity, and want to find ways to include it in every conversation, and I think that leaves a lot of people behind while we believe we're "bringing awareness". Honestly that phrase feels like a cop-out to me. It's not valueless to bring awareness to a topic, but if that's all you do, it doesn't really help anyone in the short-term. Lots of people will still fall through the cracks and be lost while the awareness of the issue is slowly sinking in without anyone just addressing the problem directly - all the actual regular people suffering right now. HELP them if you want to help them. We're aware now, let's start putting it into action.

Edit: "Bring awareness" to me feels kind of like "I'll pray for you". Assuming you believe the thing will work in either case, at best you're outsourcing your help and support to some distant force. If you don't want to go around and help individuals, at least don't assume the moral virtue that comes with helping individuals. And if you aren't helping individuals, honestly I don't know what specifically you're trying to accomplish. Are there some specific mental health industry reforms anyone is pushing for? Or does everyone just bring awareness to the fact that it's a problem?

Disclaimer, though, I'm obviously not saying people should talk less about mental health. I'm saying that, IF all you have the means to do is talk, at the very least be specific. "Bring awareness" isn't anything. To whom? Are THEY aware now? Did it help in this case? What was the actual result of any of it? 

There's more work involved in helping people than bringing awareness to the fact they need help, and I feel like this conversation has not progressed in the past 15 years to a point where people acknowledge that yet.

comment: In line with the mental health awareness I would like to share this story. I was diagnosed with anxiety my senior year of high school after a year of begging my parents to get me help for my relentless daily panic attacks. I had to give a 15 minute presentation for my English 12AP final on any subject that was of interest to me. I decided to be super vulnerable and present about anxiety disorders. I shared personal panic attack stories and statistics about how common these mental health issues are. Of course one of the jerks in class had to heckle me, saying "if everyone experiences anxiety then why can't you just get over it the way we all do", and my teacher shut him down and passed him a piece of paper that just said "serotonin". Several classmates came up to me afterwards and told me that they were so thankful for me talking about it because it helped them understand what they were feeling and made them feel less alone. I have never stopped talking about mental health since.

comment: Maybe I'm just seeing through the AP's BS, but why would a news company not want people to know the political views of their staff. We ALL have biases, and no matter how hard we may try, those biases affect the way we communicate. I firmly believe it is better to know the biases of reporters than to be kept in the dark. Sure, I get the idea that an employees tweets don't represent the views of the company they work for, but a policy that requires employees to state that the views on their socials are their own, not that of AP would be far more honest than trying to lie to the world that your writers have no biases. Something I really appreciate about the PDS, is Phil tells us his opinion (and biases). Then we know what perspective this story is being reported on from, and can look elsewhere if we want a different perspective. Pretending your employees don't have biases and opinions is just moronic.

comment:
I mean, yeah, Central Park Karen seems like a dumbass who shouldn't be allowed to own a dog, but I heard real fear in her voice. Losing your job shouldn't be the fall out from feeling scared and calling the police. Humiliation should be.

It's one thing for an entertainer _(like an actor)_ or media personality to lose their job, because their public image directly affects their job effectiveness, and another thing for a typical employment.

Instead, she should have to deal with people thinking she's an idiot who could've put a guy in real danger because of needlessly calling the police, plus any legal ramifications stemming from contacting the police. Having court mandated therapy to understand what she did wrong and how to handle situations like that seems like the right thing too.
